# Munazzam Project - Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
Munazzam is an AI-powered cognitive assistant for productivity and HR management built with MERN stack (MongoDB, Express, React, Node.js) and integrated with OpenAI/DeepSeek for AI capabilities.

## Tech Stack
- **Frontend**: React 19, Vite, Tailwind CSS, React Router, Axios
- **Backend**: Node.js, Express, MongoDB, Mongoose
- **AI**: OpenAI API, DeepSeek API, Whisper API
- **Authentication**: JWT, Passport (Google OAuth, Microsoft OAuth)
- **Deployment**: Docker, Docker Compose

## Code Style Guidelines

### General
- Use ES6+ modern JavaScript syntax
- Use async/await instead of promises chains
- Always use try-catch for error handling
- Add JSDoc comments for complex functions
- Use meaningful variable and function names in Arabic or English

### Backend (Node.js/Express)
- Use ES modules (import/export) not CommonJS (require)
- Always validate user input before processing
- Sanitize all inputs to prevent NoSQL injection
- Use middleware for authentication and authorization
- Return consistent API responses: `{ success: boolean, message: string, data?: any }`
- Use HTTP status codes correctly (200, 201, 400, 401, 403, 404, 500)
- Log errors with context information
- Never expose sensitive data in error messages

### Frontend (React)
- Use functional components with hooks
- Use React Router for navigation
- Use Axios for API calls with interceptors
- Handle loading and error states properly
- Validate forms before submission
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling
- Support RTL for Arabic language
- Never store sensitive data in localStorage (use httpOnly cookies)

### Security Best Practices
- **JWT**: Store tokens in httpOnly cookies, not localStorage
- **File Upload**: Validate file type using magic bytes, not just extension
- **Input Validation**: Validate and sanitize all user inputs
- **NoSQL Injection**: Use mongoSanitize middleware
- **XSS**: Use DOMPurify for HTML sanitization
- **CORS**: Configure CORS properly with whitelist
- **Rate Limiting**: Apply rate limiting to all API endpoints
- **API Keys**: Never commit API keys, use environment variables
- **Passwords**: Hash passwords with bcrypt (min 10 rounds)
- **HTTPS**: Always use HTTPS in production

### Database (MongoDB)
- Use Mongoose schemas with validation
- Add indexes for frequently queried fields
- Use transactions for multi-document operations
- Never expose MongoDB errors to clients
- Use projection to limit returned fields
- Implement pagination for large datasets

### API Design
- Use RESTful conventions
- Version your API (e.g., /api/v1/)
- Use plural nouns for resources (e.g., /users, /meetings)
- Use HTTP methods correctly (GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE)
- Return appropriate status codes
- Include metadata in responses (total, page, limit)

### Error Handling
- Use centralized error handling middleware
- Log errors with stack traces in development
- Return user-friendly error messages
- Never expose internal errors to clients
- Use custom error classes for different error types

### Testing
- Write unit tests for business logic
- Write integration tests for API endpoints
- Use Jest for testing
- Mock external dependencies
- Aim for 80%+ code coverage

### Documentation
- Document all API endpoints
- Use JSDoc for function documentation
- Keep README.md up to date
- Document environment variables
- Include setup instructions

## File Structure
```
munazzam/
├── client/                 # React Frontend
│   ├── src/
│   │   ├── pages/         # Page components
│   │   ├── contexts/      # React contexts
│   │   ├── services/      # API services
│   │   └── App.jsx        # Main component
│   ├── package.json
│   └── vite.config.js
├── server/                # Node.js Backend
│   ├── models/           # Mongoose models
│   ├── routes/           # Express routes
│   ├── services/         # Business logic
│   ├── middleware/       # Express middleware
│   ├── server.js         # Entry point
│   └── package.json
├── docker-compose.yml    # Docker configuration
└── README.md
```

## Environment Variables
- Never commit .env files
- Use .env.example as template
- Validate required env vars on startup
- Use strong secrets for JWT_SECRET
- Rotate API keys regularly

## Git Workflow
- Use meaningful commit messages
- Follow conventional commits format
- Create feature branches for new features
- Use pull requests for code review
- Keep commits small and focused

## Performance Optimization
- Use indexes for database queries
- Implement caching (Redis)
- Compress responses (gzip)
- Optimize images and assets
- Use CDN for static files
- Implement lazy loading
- Use code splitting

## Monitoring and Logging
- Log all errors with context
- Monitor API response times
- Track user actions
- Set up alerts for critical errors
- Use structured logging (JSON)

## Deployment
- Use Docker for containerization
- Use environment-specific configs
- Implement health checks
- Use reverse proxy (Nginx)
- Enable HTTPS with Let's Encrypt
- Set up automated backups
- Implement CI/CD pipeline

## Common Patterns

### API Response Format
```javascript
// Success
{
  success: true,
  message: "عملية ناجحة",
  data: { ... }
}

// Error
{
  success: false,
  message: "حدث خطأ",
  error: "تفاصيل الخطأ" // only in development
}
```

### Error Handling Pattern
```javascript
try {
  // Your code here
} catch (error) {
  console.error('Context:', error);
  return res.status(500).json({
    success: false,
    message: 'رسالة خطأ واضحة للمستخدم'
  });
}
```

### Authentication Pattern
```javascript
// Protect routes with middleware
router.get('/protected', protect, async (req, res) => {
  // req.user is available here
});
```

### Validation Pattern
```javascript
// Validate input before processing
if (!email || !password) {
  return res.status(400).json({
    success: false,
    message: 'الرجاء إدخال جميع الحقول المطلوبة'
  });
}
```

